The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport

 Monday, April 11, 2005 

 New Delhi: Arvind Bhat failed in his bid to add another international title to his kitty as he went down to local favourite and top seed Prezemyslaw Wacha in the final of the Polish Open badminton championship at Spala in Poland on Sunday.

 Bhat, who had accounted for second seed Joachim Persson of Denmark on his way to the summit clash, failed to maintain the momentum and went down 15-8, 15-7 in a 45-minute encounter of this grade A event. Bhat reached the final by defeating Jens-Kristien Leth of Denmark 15-11, 15-7.

 Wacha was the man who ended the run of even the other two Indians in the fray. In the semi-final, he defeated Thomas Kurien 15-4 15-7, in just 27 minutes. In the pre-quarters, he beat Anup Sridhar 15-9, 12-15, 15-12.

 New Delhi: Seven-time world billiards champion and the country?s most popular cueist Geet Sethi on Sunday has called for the inclusion of cue sports in the 2010 Commonwealth Games to be held here and said he would like to represent the country in those Games.

 The Billiards and Snooker Federation of India has been making an all out effort to get the sport included in the 2010 games and has already sent a proposal to the Indian Olympic Association in this regard.

 Karachi: The three-match tsunami relief hockey series between Pakistan and India has been postponed, officials said on Sunday.

 ?The series has been postponed for reasons beyond our control. Fresh dates will be announced after consulation with Indian Hockey Federation,? Pakistan hockey federation secretary Musarratullah Khan said from Lahore.

 The matches were proposed for April 22, 25 and 28.

 ?The series has not been cancelled but postponed for the time being,? Musarratullah stressed.

 The earnings from this series was to go to President Pervez Musharrafs tsunami relief fund.

 Amelia Island: Serena Williams is keen to play for the US in their first-round Fed Cup tie against Belgium later this month despite spraining her left ankle on Friday. She is scheduled to join sister Venus, world No. 1 Lindsay Davenport and Corina Morariu for the April 23-24 tie.

 However, she faces a race to get fit in time after spraining her ankle during the quarters of the Amelia Island meet against Italian Silvia Farina Elia. The 23-year-old is set to undergo intensive physiotherapy and will make a final decision nearer the time. 

 Bucharest: Players from Romanian soccer club CFR Cluj were injured when fans of visiting team Apulum Alba Iulia attacked them on the street, the club?s president said on Saturday.

 Iuliu Muresan said the supporters hit and punched his team?s players with sticks as they were leaving a restaurant. He added his club will make an official complaint to the police and the Romanian federation.

 Doha: The IAAF?s executive council wants to spend an additional $650,000 to keep its sports clean of doping. The body, which met on Saturday, spends nearly $ 2m on anti-doping efforts. The decision must be approved at the IAAF congress, which will meet on August 3 and 4 before the world championships.

